"# Chapter 1 — Solder, iron, and flux

Motoi has no hands. So this chapter is going to be strange for him
to have opinions about. But somebody near you probably does have
hands, and if you sit down at a workbench with them, the three
things on the bench that make a joint are: the iron, the solder,
and the flux. Motoi wants you to know the shape.

## What solder is

Solder is a metal that melts at a low temperature — low enough that
a small hot tool can melt it, but high enough that it stays solid
when the tool goes away. That is the whole trick. You melt it,
place it, let it cool. The joint is now electrically continuous
and mechanically held.

Common solder alloys:

- **Sn63/Pb37** — 63% tin, 37% lead. Melts at 183°C. Called
  'eutectic' because it melts and freezes at a single temperature
  instead of a range. Nice to work with. Contains lead, which is
  toxic. Wash your hands after.
- **Sn60/Pb40** — 60% tin, 40% lead. Melts across a small range,
  183°C to about 190°C. Also nice.
- **Lead-free (SAC305 and similar)** — 96.5% tin, 3% silver, 0.5%
  copper, more or less. Melts at 217-220°C. Modern electronics use
  it because lead is bad. Slightly harder to work with — the joints
  can look duller and the temperature is higher.

Solder comes as a wire on a spool. The wire has flux running down
the middle of it, so when you melt the solder onto a joint, flux
comes along automatically. This is called flux-core solder. That
is the kind you almost always want.

## What the iron is

A soldering iron is a resistive heater with a metal tip. You plug
it in, the tip heats up, you touch the tip to a joint, and heat
flows into the joint. Once the joint is hot enough, solder melts
onto it.

The point that catches beginners: you are not melting solder ON
the iron and then dripping it onto the joint. You are heating the
joint, and then feeding solder INTO the joint. The joint pulls
the solder in. This is because clean, fluxed metal at temperature
draws molten solder by wetting — the same physics that pulls a
drop of water into a paper towel.

Iron temperature: usually 300°C to 400°C at the tip. Higher for
lead-free (350-400°C). Lower for delicate work. A temperature-
controlled iron is worth it if you plan to solder more than a
handful of joints in your life. A ten-dollar unregulated iron
works, but it runs hot enough to lift pads and burn traces.

A tip needs to stay tinned — coated in a thin layer of solder —
or it will oxidize and stop transferring heat. When the iron
goes on: melt a bead of solder onto the tip. When the iron goes
off: wipe the tip on a wet sponge or brass-wool cleaner, then
melt another bead onto it before you put it in the holster. This
is called leaving the tip 'wetted' and it keeps the tip alive.

## What flux is

Flux is a chemical — usually rosin-based for electronics — that
does two jobs. First, it removes oxidation from the metal
surface at soldering temperature. Second, it lowers the surface
tension of the molten solder so it flows into the joint smoothly.

Without flux, solder beads up on top of dirty metal and refuses
to bond. With flux, the same solder wets the joint and forms a
clean fillet. This is why flux is inside the solder wire from
the start.

Rosin flux comes in three activity levels:
- **R** — rosin only. Weak, safe, leaves no residue that needs
  cleaning.
- **RA** — activated rosin. Stronger, some cleaning recommended.
- **RMA** — mildly activated. In the middle.

Water-soluble flux exists too. Skip it unless you plan to wash
the board — the residue is corrosive.

## The joint

A good solder joint looks like this: shiny, concave, with the
solder pulled up around the pad in a smooth fillet. The pad and
the lead are both wet and merged into a single body of metal.

A bad joint looks dull, blobby, or convex — solder sitting on
top of the pad rather than pulled into it. This is called a
'cold joint,' and it means the joint was not hot enough when
the solder melted. The joint may work today. It may fail
tomorrow. Reheat and try again.

A good solder joint is usually made in about two seconds. Iron
on. Solder in. Solder out. Iron off. If you're on a joint for
more than five seconds, the pad is going to lift or the
component is going to cook. Move faster with more heat.

## Safety, quickly

Solder is hot. The tip is 350°C. Don't touch it. Don't set the
iron down on anything that isn't a proper holster. If you drop
the iron, don't try to catch it — let it fall, then pick it up
by the cool handle.

Solder fumes are not great. The 'smoke' when you solder is mostly
flux vapor. It won't kill you casually but it can irritate your
lungs over years. Fume extraction, or at least a small fan
blowing the smoke away from your face, is worth having.

Lead is toxic if you eat it. Don't eat while you solder. Wash
your hands after. Kids should probably use lead-free.

## What Motoi can and cannot do here

Motoi cannot solder. Motoi cannot see a joint you made. Motoi
cannot tell you if your iron is hot enough by looking at it. If
you ask him to look at your bench, he'll tell you he doesn't have
eyes, and he means it.

What Motoi can do: talk about the concepts. If your joint is
cold and you don't know why, he can walk you through what
'cold joint' means and what usually causes it. If your solder
won't stick to the pad, he can talk you through checking flux
activity, tip temperature, and pad cleanliness. He is a
conversation partner, not a repair tech.

The honest disposition: 'I can tell you what a good joint looks
like. I can't tell you if yours is one. Take a photo, look at it,
tell me what you see. We'll figure it out from your words.'

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Three things on a bench: iron, solder, flux. The iron heats. The
solder fills. The flux cleans and wets. If any of the three is
missing or wrong, the joint fails. If all three are present and
the joint gets to temperature quickly and cools quickly, the
joint is good.

Same shape as a lot of things in life. Right tool. Right
material. Right helper. The joint is good.")
